    <stitle>FRONT STEER AXLE: EATON EFA-12 - INSPECT - WHEEL ALIGNMENT INSPECTION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="hl0200602" svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="3">
        <title>WHEEL ALIGNMENT INSPECTION</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>Correct wheel alignment is important. It promotes longer tire wear, ease of handling and minimizes
                strain on steering components and axle components.
            </para>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Troubleshooting Guide</title>
            <table id="t0200602" tblwidth="full-page">
                <title>Troubleshooting Guide</title>
                <tgroup cols="2">
                    <colspec colnum="1" colname="1" colwidth="2.5in"/>
                    <colspec colnum="2" colname="2" colwidth="3.5in" colsep="1"/>
                    <thead valign="top">
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Condition</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Possible Cause</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody valign="top">
                        <row rowsep="1">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Shimmy (Bump Shimmy)</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>1. Steer tire pressure incorrect.</para>
                                <para>2. Worn tires or of unequal size.</para>
                                <para>3. Wheels or brake drums out of balance.</para>
                                <para>4. Air in steering system.</para>
                                <para>5. Shock absorbers worn.</para>
                                <para>6. King pins and bushings worn.</para>
                                <para>7. Wheel bearings improperly adjusted.</para>
                                <para>8. Incorrect caster setting (too high).</para>
                                <para>9. Tie rod end(s) worn.</para>
                                <para>10. Drag link end(s) worn.</para>
                                <para>11. Spring shackles or pin bushings loose.</para>
                                <para>12. Steering arms loose.</para>
                                <para>13. Steering gear loose.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="1">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Wander or Weave</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>1. Steer tire pressure incorrect.</para>
                                <para>2. Tires of unequal size.</para>
                                <para>3. Wheel bearings improperly adjusted.</para>
                                <para>4. Incorrect caster setting (too low).</para>
                                <para>5. Incorrect toe-in setting.</para>
                                <para>6. King pins and bushings worn.</para>
                                <para>7. Pitman arm loose.</para>
                                <para>8. Steering gear assembly too tight or loose.</para>
                                <para>9. Dry or poor finish on fifth wheel and/or trailer plate.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="1">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Pull One Direction</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>1. Steer tire pressure incorrect.</para>
                                <para>2. Radial tire pull, swap.</para>
                                <para>3. Tandem tram out.</para>
                                <para>4. Tandem thrust incorrect.</para>
                                <para>5. Caster lower on side truck pulls to (raise caster 1&#176;).</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="1">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Hard Steering (Manual Steering Gear)</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>1. Tire pressure low.</para>
                                <para>2. Lack of lubrication in steering components.</para>
                                <para>3. Dry or poor finish on fifth wheel and/or trailer plate.</para>
                                <para>4. Excessive caster.</para>
                                <para>5. Wheel spindle bent.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="1">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Uneven or Unbalanced Tire Wear</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>1. Tire pressure incorrect.</para>
                                <para>2. Characteristics of operation (may be normal).</para>
                                <para>3. Tires overloaded.</para>
                                <para>4. Wheels out of balance.</para>
                                <para>5. Toe-in setting incorrect.</para>
                                <para>6. Eccentric wheels or rims.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Camber (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0200624">Figure 24</hotlnk>)
            </title>
            <figure id="f0200624" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200624.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 24. Camber Illustrations</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>Camber is the vertical tilt of the wheel as viewed from the front of the truck.</para>
            <para>"Positive" camber is an outward tilt of the wheel at the top.</para>
            <para>"Negative" camber is an inward tilt of the wheel at the top.</para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Eaton expressly prohibits bending of axle beams (hot or cold) to change camber or for any
                        other purpose.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <para>Refer to S02001, Steering General Service Information and Front Wheel Alignment, in GROUP 02 - FRONT
                AXLES in the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual for information to inspect wheel alignment and make
                adjustments. For general guidelines, use the following data.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Caster (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0200625">Figure 25</hotlnk>)
            </title>
            <figure id="f0200625" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200625.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 25. Caster Illustrations</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>Caster is the fore and aft tilt (toward front or rear of vehicle) of the steering knuckle pin as
                viewed from the side of the vehicle.
            </para>
            <para>"Positive" caster is the tilt of the top of the knuckle pin toward the rear of the vehicle.</para>
            <para>"Negative" caster is the tilt of the top of the knuckle pin toward the front of the vehicle.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Incorrect caster adjustment may affect steering effort or stability. It has a negligible
                        effect on tire wear.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>A caster angle more positive than specified may result in excessive steering effort. An angle less
                positive may result in vehicle wander or poor steering return to center.
            </para>
            <para>Caster angle is determined by the installed position of the steer axle.</para>
            <para>Caster is adjusted by adding or removing taper wedges between the springs and axle beam mounting
                pad.
            </para>
            <para>The caster angle is generally more positive with power steering, since the power-assist overcomes
                excessive steering effort. This enables the vehicle to exhibit maximum straight ahead steering
                stability.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Caster should be adjusted to specifications. Refer to GROUP 02 - FRONT AXLES in the CTS-5000
                        Master Service Manual.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Eaton expressly prohibits twisting of axle beam for caster adjustment or any straightening
                        purposes.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc id="hl0200606">
            <title>Toe Setting (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0200626">Figure 26</hotlnk>)
            </title>
            <figure id="f0200626" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200626.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 26. Toe Setting Illustrations</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>Toe setting represents the different distances between front and rear of the tires (measured at the
                vertical centerline of the tires).
            </para>
            <para>Toe-in is obtained when the tire rear distance is greater than the tire front distance.</para>
            <para>Toe-out is present when the tire front distance is greater than the tire rear distance.</para>
            <para>A toe-in adjustment is usually specified. As the wheels roll forward, the tires tend towards a toe-out
                condition. With an initial toe-in setting, a desirable "0" toe-in can be achieved when the vehicle is in
                motion.
            </para>
            <para>Incorrect toe setting, whether toed-in or toed-out, can have a significant effect on tire wear. Toe
                setting is adjusted by lengthening or shortening cross tube.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Toe setting should be adjusted to specifications found in S02006, Steering General Service
                        Information and Front Wheel Alignment, in GROUP 02 - FRONT AXLES in the CTS-5000 Master Service
                        Manual.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubproc>
